SGB finds student rep for search committee

By Stephen Kozarovich
Asst. News Editor

Pitt’s Student Government Board announced its appointment of a
new student representative to the provost search committee at last
night’s meeting.

After a short deliberation, Pitt junior Heather Heinrichs was cho-
sen to fill the position vacated by former SGB President Jacob
Brody, who resigned the position after taking a full—time job.

“I’m extremely happy with the decision,” Heinrichs said. “I’m
very ﬂattered that they chose me.”

Heinrichs is working toward a self—designed pre-medical major.
She is currently a member of the Golden Key and Phi Eta Sigma
honor societies.

She will also take over as president of the Blue and Gold Society

at the end of this semester and serve on the Alumni Association
Board of Directors.

Heinrichs said she decided to apply for the position after seeing
an advertisement to do so in The Pitt News.

“I thought it was very important to get student input in a decision
like this,” Heinrichs said.

Heinrichs has also served on the SGB Elections Committee for
two years.

“Heather and I are the only two students on the Board of
Directors of the Alumni Association,” SGB President Ross Pasquale
said, “and having viewed her in that capacity, I feel very comfort-
able that she is able to interact well with administrators.”

According to SGB, Heinrichs time availability, her commitment to
campus involvement and experience in dealing with Pitt’s adminis-
tration inﬂuenced the board's decision.

IFC schedules dates for fall rush in anticipation

By Sam Gresock

News Assistant

Though Pitt’s Inter-Fraternity
Council just recently closed the
final chapter on its spring rush,
plans have already begun for
next fall’s recruitment schedule.

The IFC voted last night on its
rush dates for the Fall 1994 term,
which will be held Sept. 7-15.

The week of Sept. 14-22 was
also discussed as a possible
recruitment period, but the dates

coincided with the sorority
rush’s proposed schedule of
Sept. 16-25.

IFC President Brian Rifkin said
the schedule should benefit fra-
ternities who hold rush func-
tions with sororities, since it is
unlikely sororities would attend
fraternity events during their
own rush. “I think the big ques-
tion is whether we want to
[invite] sororities during rush or
do we want to have rush, and
then not have sororities until

later,” Rifkin said.

The IFC will probably not
have to face the sub—zero tem-
peratures and snowfall this fall
that occurred during its spring
rush Jan. 12-20. Due in part to a
reduced turnout at mid—January’s
rush events, the IFC sponsored a
second spring rush Feb. 7-10.

According to IFC Vice
President for Recruitment Andy
Demming, eight students took
advantage of last week’s “second
chance” recruitment period.

“It wasn’t supposed to be a
rush to get large numbers,”
Demming said. “There were just
a couple of houses that needed
a couple more guys to keep
their numbers up. It worked
good for the houses that needed
it.”

This spring’s rush, including
last week’s extension, netted a
total of 106 students. The num-
bers mark a decrease from the
156 students who joined the
Greek system in spring of 1995.

