By Jonathan Kersting
For The Pitt News

Senior citizens have the
opportunity to learn a variety of
subjects from the arts to the sci-
ences.

Pitt’s Over Sixty Program
allows senior citizens to attend
class on an audit basis so they
can actively participate in class
without receiving a grade.

Jan White, director of the
Over Sixty Program, said the
program has been in operation
for the past 12 years. White
reserves four seats per class in
various classes in the College of
General Studies for the program

members. The cost for each
class is $15.

This past fall term had the
largest attendance ever with 560
students, White said. This terrn’s
attendance has dropped slightly
to 517 students.

“What a great thing, to learn
something I like,” said Gerry
Hart.

Hart graduated from West
Point Military Academy and
played professional football for
the 1953 Detroit Lions. He is
now retired, after 31 years of
service at J&L Steel, and is
attending a French 11 class, his
first college class in over 40
years.

He got the ‘idea to at-
tend classes here at Pitt from
a friend of his who also at-
tends classes. Students over
the age of 60 generally register
in one or two classes per
semester. They want to stay
busy, but not too busy, accord-
ing to Hart.

Attending college classes
enables many senior citizens
to study subjects that they
have always wanted to
study, but have never had the
time.

Tim Miller, a serni-retired
small business owner, said he
has been wanting to attend
some law classes for the past

couple of years, but has not yet
found the time.

Not all senior citizens are sold
on the idea of returning to
school. Harry Wilker, a 75-year-
old native Pittsburgher, said he
has “no interest in going back
to school.”

He said he has learned
enough over the years from his
business associates.

Just in case Wilker ever has a
change of heart, the more typi-
cal college-aged students seem
to welcome their elders attend-
ing class alongside them.

Benita Hunter, a science
major, said, ‘‘It‘s great that they
want to come back and learn.”

  

