All for our children's crusade

It seems like every day a new controversy arises
surrounding the issue of individuals and their consti-
tutional rights.

Here at Pitt, as an example close to home, ques-
tions are surfacing again about possible censorship at
the Pitt Program Council art exhibition because of the
university’s refusal to accept “sexually explicit” art.

Whenever civil rights are broken and whenever
institutions try to implement moral judgements, then
individuals are often forced to do battle against pow-
erful organizations. When the victims of these prob-
lems are teenagers and children, though, then unfor-
tunately individuals’ rights can be even easier to vio-
late.

This is what happened to the six teenagers from the
New Castle Area School District who claim that they
were strip—searched by school officials at Ben
Franklin Junior High School in December, 1992. On
Monday, Maceo Hill, 17, testified in U.S. District
Court that he was forced take off his shirt and pants
and pull his underwear up to his chest so that he
could be searched for drugs, which were not found
(Pittsburgh Post-Gazette).

The school district’s attorney admits that the search-
es occurred, but he said that not all the students were
forced to remove their clothes and that they were not
exactly “strip” searches (Post-Gazette). But regardless
of the number of searches and the technicality of the
term “strip—search,” constitutional rights were still bla-
tantly violated.

A judge has determined that the searches were an
infringement of the Fourth Amendment (unlegal
search and seizure) and the 14th Amendment (due
process of the law), but the trial will decide whether
or not the school officials can be held liable for these
violations, (Post-Gazette).

All school officials have taken on the responsibility
of children while they are in school. Therefore, these
officials must be held responsible when they break
the law and ignore the rights of these students.
People under 18 are told over and over to respect
authority, but apparently the authorities need to be
told to respect the children.

Many people say that today’s youth are in desperate
need of care and education. Instead, these school
officials have shown that they don’t care about the
students’ rights, but they_have taught them ﬂagrant
disregard of the law.

The adults that were involved with the searches
should be punished. Younger individuals must fight
harder to be heard, so the courts should work harder
to ensure their rights. Punishment for those who have
broken the law is necessary to end the exploitation of
youth. .

